        "## 6. PatchTST — the Hugging Face Transformer (→ thesis Ch. 4.3, RQ2)\n",
        "\n",
        "**PatchTST** (Nie et al., 2023; implemented in Hugging Face `transformers`, Wolf et al., 2020) applies two ideas: **patching** — the input series is cut into overlapping sub-series \"tokens\" (here patch length 8, stride 4 → 14 tokens from a 63-day context), which preserves local structure and reduces the quadratic attention cost — and **channel independence** — one shared univariate model per channel. A small configuration (**d_model 64, 3 layers, 4 heads, FFN 128, dropout 0.2; ≈ 50k parameters**) is deliberate: with ≈ 4,400 training windows per index, a large model would overfit.\n",
        "\n",
        "Training: manual per-index standardization using **train-block statistics only** (in-model scaling disabled so the inverse transform is fully under our control), AdamW (lr $10^{-3}$), batch 64, ≤ 30 epochs, early stopping on validation MSE (patience 5), fixed seed. All matrix products run on **CUDA** through PyTorch (Paszke et al., 2019) — this is the GPU dependence that Section 7 quantifies."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "g7uAIaSC5VeE"
      }
    },
