        "## 8. Out-of-sample evaluation (→ thesis Ch. 5.1–5.3, RQ2)\n",
        "\n",
        "Metrics on the test block: **RMSE** and **MAE** on log volatility, and — the headline criterion — **QLIKE** on the variance level,\n",
        "$$\\mathrm{QLIKE} = \\frac{RV_t}{F_t} - \\ln\\frac{RV_t}{F_t} - 1, \\qquad RV_t = e^{2x_t},\\ F_t = e^{2\\hat{x}_t},$$\n",
        "which Patton (2011) shows delivers consistent rankings even when the volatility proxy is noisy (exactly our Garman–Klass setting).\n",
        "\n",
        "Significance: **Diebold–Mariano (1995)** on per-observation loss differentials with Newey–West variance (Bartlett weights, bandwidth $h-1$) and the **Harvey–Leybourne–Newbold (1997)** small-sample correction; Student-$t$ p-values. Sign convention: **negative DM statistic ⇒ the first model (PatchTST) has the lower loss.** With 15 pairwise tests, interpret patterns rather than isolated $p<0.05$."
      ],
